 \par\nointerlineskip  #4%

%%
\makeatletter
\renewcommand*\env@matrix[1][\arraystretch]{%
  \edef\arraystretch{#1}%

%%

%%
%% ENUMERATION and ITEMIZATION
%%

\usepackage[inline]{enumitem}

%% Configuring enumitem
%   CAVE: 1) the \setlist global values for a single list must be defined in a SINGLE \setlist command as they otherwise get overwritten by defaults again
%         2) the settings do not carry over to \newlist defined custom lists
%         3) for the starred inline versions the settings are carried over from the non-starred to the starred versions
%         4) for \newlist defined custom lists the settings do not carry over from the non-starred to the starred versions
%         SIGH !

\setlist{itemjoin={\hspace{0.5cm}}}%                     bit of space as joiner for the inline version

\def\enumerateWithDots{
  \setlist[enumerate]{
    partopsep=1.0\parskip,  % separation added when the preceding is a paragraph
    topsep=-0.5\parskip,    % separation added when the preceding is only a line with no paragraph ending
    itemsep=0cm,
    label=\textbf{(\arabic*)},
    after={\vspace*{1.5\parskip}}
  }
}

\def\enumerateWithBrackets{
  \setlist[enumerate]{
    partopsep=1.0\parskip,  % separation added when the preceding is a paragraph
    topsep=-0.5\parskip,    % separation added when the preceding is only a line with no paragraph ending
    itemsep=0cm,
    label=\textbf{(\arabic*)},
    after={\vspace*{1.5\parskip}}
  }
}

\enumerateWithBrackets


%% define enumerated as dotted version should we nevertheless need it.
\newlist{enumerated}{enumerate}{3}\setlist[enumerated]{topsep=0pt,itemsep=0cm,label=\textbf{\arabic*.}}  
\newlist{enumerated*}{enumerate*}{3}\setlist[enumerated*]{topsep=0pt,itemsep=0cm,label=\textbf{\arabic*.}} % need that since for custom lists the * automatism does not work

\setlist[itemize]{
  partopsep=1.0\parskip,
  topsep=-0.5\parskip,
  itemsep=0cm
}

\setlist[description]{itemindent=-1.5em, labelsep=0pt,partopsep=\parskip,topsep=-\parskip}

We cannota say that the object is (or is in the state) $\omega$ as this description might not be precise enough in the sense that the object might have additional properties as well (The color red is an insufficient characterization of an object). We have the fantasy that a sufficient number of properties will uniquely describe an object (This fantasy might not be true). We used language to assign the property to the object but we should rather have used language which assigns the property to the relation of both, the measurement device and the object. And we should not ignore that, in addition to measurement device and object there is also a certain rest in the universe. In the end, we should talk about the property being connected to the measurement device, the object and the rest of the universe. However, it is more convenient, at least in the beginning, to assume that the property belongs to the object alone and take the journey from there. Also,lkj we must admit that there are observations (Hon Mandel dip) and theories (particle number operator not always precisely defined in Fock space) which make it difficult to talk about well-defined objects, of which we have the fantasy that they can be identified, and even if they do not carry identity that the at least could be counted in numbers of a kind.
We make the observation: If we measure a property twice immediately after each other leaving no time for development in between, we get the same result. This might not be the case for every measurement (there are measuremetns for which this is not true and where we describe the measurement as an interaction which changes the object in a way and there are measurements which cannot be made twice in a row as, for example, they destroy the measured object by the very act of observation -- at least that is how we describe the situations in these cases), but at least we can assume this for a class of ideal measurements.
Under this assumption: After the measurement we talk about the property of the object in a precise manner in the sense that a repeated measurement leads to the same result.
So, how would we describe the object before the measurement?
Assume we make the observation, that an object may lead to different measurement results. We find: When we measure (different) objects of a certain kind of which we believe we know no difference (short of knowing somehow that they are different), why would they lead to different measurement results.
a Even worse: We assumed that we knew a property after the measurement. So we know the object as such.
We can describe this as: One property is still missing which we did not measure in that measurement (for example we measured color and not smell) and if we had measured it we would have realized that the object is indeed different. We can describe this as: Before the measurement the object did not have the property we measured (it was imprinted by the measurement). Before the measurement the object had that property only to a certain degree, and for some reason the measurement process selected this and not that aspect of the property. </amsmath>

revision.text: == Parsifal Cheat Sheet == == Editor == If the editor frame window is focused, adjust the font size of the editor using Cmd + or Cmd - without resizing the rest of the browser. === Attributes === ==== Collapse ==== ==== Continuation ==== Situation: We want to split TeX text into several smaller portions. Advantages of this are: * Faster preview * Smaller unit of error and unit of editing * Seperate edit link For the presentation, there can be several scenarios: * Separation: We want a bit of markup which lets the reader see that there are two different portions of text. * Continuation: We do not want to indicate this separation into two different portions of text. The second portion should be a seamless continuation of the first text. Nevertheless there should be a possibility for the reader to recognize the two parts and to invoke edit links and similar actions for the two parts. [[Category:DanteInitialContents]]

revision.comment: /* Why is this called DanteWiki? */
revision.text:
== FAQ ==
=== Why is this called DanteWiki? === The thought of writing done what one has understood dates back to Dante:
"O mente, che scrivesti ci√≤ ch‚Äôio vidi" (Dante, Inferno II, 8)
"O Ged√§chtnis, das geschrieben, was ich erkannte" (own translation)
This thought has also been described in a letter of Nicolo Machiavelli to Francesco Vettori, florentinian ambassador in Rome. We cite it here according to Niccolo Machiavelli, Der F√ºrst. Suhrkamp Verlag, 2016:
<poem> Und weil Dante sagt, es gebe keine Wissenschaft ohne die Aufzeichnung dessen, was man begriffen hat ‚Äì so habe ich das notiert, was ich bei dem Gespr√§ch mit Ihnen als das Wesentliche festhielt, und ein kleines Werk √ºber F√ºrstent√ºmer verfa√üt, worin ich mich so weit wie m√∂glich in die Gedanken √ºber dieses Thema vertiefe und er√∂rtere, was Herrschaft ist, welche Arten es davon gib, wie man sie erwirbt und erh√§lt und warum man sie verliert. </poem>
Or, for short:
"[E]s [gibt] keine Wissenschaft ohne die Aufzeichnung dessen, was man begriffen hat."
"There is no science without a record of what one has understood" (own translation)
That's why I call this Wiki system a DanteWiki.
=== What does the logo show? === The logo shows a painting made by Michelangelo Merisi da Caravaggio in 1607. It depicts Saint Jerome of Stridon, who is best known for his translations of the Bible into Latin. it here serves as the symbol of a scientist, philosopher and thinker. Saint Jerome is alone, remote from the distractions of the world, focused alone on putting down his thoughts. The skull on his table reminds us of the mortality of man and the volatility of his thoughts. It thus challenges us to write down our thoughts.
The logo thus reflexts my core motives when creating this system.
=== What is the relation to MediaWiki? === None.
I did not want to build this system completely from scratch. MediaWiki was the software which contained most of the necessary base functionality and was open for further development due to its open license model. I will try to keep DanteWiki as close to MediaWiki as possible to ease maintenence and bug fixing.
=== What is the relation to WikiPedia? === None.
While WikiPedia is a very interesting project, I do not subscribe to the objectivist perspective on which it seems to be grounded. In particular - in my opinion - the neutral point of view goal of WikiPedia cannot be achieved for a number of linguistic reasons and should not be aimed for due to a number of philosophic reasons.
DanteWiki follows different goals and guidelines.

\textbf{Stack:} 
\begin{itemize}
\item Selbe Aufgabe wie in jedem akzeptzierenden Keller-Automaten.
\item Konvention: Stack w√§chst von links nach rechts. \\
Damit √§ndert das Bef√ºllen des Stacks nicht die Leserichtung.\\
Das macht die reduce Schritte einfacher.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Heap:} 
\begin{itemize}
\item Bereich zur Konstruktion von Teilen des Ableitungsbaums.
\item Zus√§tzlich zur Funktion des akzeptierenden Keller-Automaten.
\item Kann auch vom Stack mit √ºbernommen werden,\\ wenn dieser nicht nur Symbole speichert sondern auch Zeiger auf Teilb√§ume.
\end{itemize}

Aktionen des Parsers:
 
\textbf{Shift:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Entferne das n√§chste Symbol vom Input.
\item Baue aus diesem Symbol einen neuen einknotigen Parsebaum.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Reduce:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Wende eine Grammatikregel auf Top of Stack (liegt rechts!) an.
\item Fasse die betroffenen Symbole zu einem Parsebaum zusammen.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Terminate:}
\begin{enumerate}
\item Der Input ist leer (kein weiterer Shift √úbergang ist mehr m√∂glich).
\item Kein weiterer Reduce √úbergang ist mehr m√∂glich.
\item Es liegt nur mehr das Startsymbol auf dem Stack.
\end{enumerate}



</amsmath>

== Beispiel ==
<amsmath sans>
\def\to{\mbox{$\rightarrow$ }}
\def\r#1{{\color{red}#1}}

Die Grammatik habe als Terminale die Token $\{$ \r{ID}, \r{INT}, \r{*}, \r{+}, \r{=} $\}$. \\
Lexikalische Auspr√§gungen der Token \r{ID} seien $\{$ A, B, C, D $\}$.\\
Lexikalische Auspr√§gungen der Token \r{INT} seien $\{$ 1, 2, 3, 4 $\}$.\\
Die √ºbrigen Token stehen lexikalisch f√ºr sich selbst.

Die Grammatik habe die Nichtterminale $\{$ Val, Prod, Sum, Ass $\}$.

Startsymbol sei Ass.

Die Grammatik sei gegeben durch die Regeln:

\mright\begin{minipage}{10cm}
Val \to \r{ID} \\
Val \to \r{INT} \\
Prod \to Val \\
Prod \to Prod \r{*} Val \\
Sum \to Prod \\
Sum \to Sum \r{+} Prod \\
Ass \to \r{ID} \r{=} Sum
\end{minipage}

Zu parsen sei die Eingabe A = B + C * 2
 

\begin{tabular}[]{llllll}
\textbf{Nr.} & \textbf{Stack} & \textbf{LA} & \textbf{Input-Buffer} &  \textbf{Action} \\ 
1&        &  \r{ID(A)} & A = B + C * 2 & Shift ID(A) \\
2&\r{ID}  &  \r=  &  = B + C * 2 & Shift =\\
3& \r{ID} \r{=} & \r{ID(B)}    &  B + C * 2 & Shift ID(B)\\
4&\r{ID} \r{=} \r{ID}& \r+ & + C * 2 & Reduce  Val \to ID\\
5&\r{ID} \r{=}   Val & \r+ &  + C * 2 & Reduce Prod \to Val \\
6&\r{ID} \r{=} Prod  & \r{+} & + C * 2 & Reduce Sum \to Prod \\
7&\r{ID}  \r{=} Sum   & \r{+} & + C * 2 & Shift +\\
8&\r{ID} \r{=}  Sum \r{+} & \r{ID(C)}  & C * 2 & Shift ID(C) \\
9&\r{ID} \r{=} Sum \r{+} \r{ID}& \r{*} & * 2 & Reduce Val \to ID\\
10&\r{ID} \r{=} Sum \r{+} Val & \r{*}& * 2 & Reduce Prod \to Val \\
11&\r{ID} \r{=} Sum \r{+} Prod  & \r{*} & * 2  & Shift * \\
12&\r{ID} \r{=} Sum  \r{+} Prod \r{*} & \r{INT(2)} & 2 & Shift INT(2) \\

17 & Ass &  &  &Terminate Startsymbol Ass
\end{tabular}

\textbf{Wesentlich:} 
Es \textit{existiert} ein solcher Ablauf im Keller-Automaten.

Dieser Ablauf im Keller-Automaten entspricht der folgenden Rechts-Ableitung:

Ass \\ 
\to ID = \underline{Sum} \\ 
\to ID = Sum + \underline{Prod} \\
\to ID = Sum + Prod * \underline{Val} \\
\to ID = Sum + \underline{Prod} * INT\\
\to ID = Sum + \underline{Val} * INT\\
\to ID = \underline{Sum} + ID * INT\\
\to ID = \underline{Prod} + ID * INT\\
\to ID = \underline{Val} + ID * INT\\
\to ID = ID + ID * INT
